  <h2>The Brief</h2>
  <p>
    Industrial cleaning is categorically different from commercial cleaning in its safety obligations, workforce requirements and operational constraints. A provider competent in office buildings, retail centres or education facilities is not automatically competent in an environment where the cleaning workforce operates alongside active plant, manages combustible dust accumulation, enters confined spaces, and works during shutdown and maintenance windows that are scheduled around production requirements rather than cleaning convenience.
  </p>
  <p>
    For mining equipment maintenance facilities, power generation infrastructure and heavy industrial operations, the cleaning provider is not a peripheral supplier — they are a participant in the site's safety management system. Their workforce must be inducted to the site's safety standards, their method statements must be assessed against site-specific hazards, and their supervisors must be capable of integrating cleaning activities with the permit-to-work system that governs all activities in high-risk industrial environments.
  </p>

  <h2>The Approach</h2>
  <p>
    CPC's industrial cleaning approach begins with hazard identification at the site level. Before deploying a workforce to any industrial facility, CPC conducts a site-specific hazard assessment and develops documented safe work method statements for each hazard category present — dust, confined spaces, working at heights, chemical handling, proximity to operating plant, and any site-specific hazards identified during assessment.
  </p>
  <p>
    The trained and compliance-screened workforce deployed to industrial sites completes site-specific induction and hazard-specific training before commencing work. This is not a standard commercial cleaning induction extended to an industrial context — it is industrial safety training calibrated to the specific facility type, hazard profile and permit-to-work requirements of each site.
  </p>
  <p>
    Scheduling industrial cleaning around production requirements is a distinct operational capability. Shutdown and outage periods — the windows when cleaning of process areas, equipment internals and high-risk zones is possible — are coordinated with the client's maintenance scheduling team. This requires supervisors who understand production and maintenance timelines, not just cleaning schedules.
  </p>

  <h2>The Operation</h2>
  <p>
    CPC's industrial portfolio includes multi-site cleaning operations for major Australian mining equipment maintenance operators. These facilities — large-scale maintenance workshops handling heavy mining equipment — generate significant dust, chemical and workshop waste, and operate with cleaning requirements that must integrate with production maintenance schedules across multiple locations nationally.
  </p>
  <p>
    Power generation facility experience in the CPC portfolio includes cleaning operations at Queensland power generation infrastructure, where coal dust management, outage-period deep cleaning and the permit-to-work system of a generating facility create compliance requirements beyond the capacity of general commercial cleaning providers. Outage-period cleaning requires coordination with the facility's maintenance shutdown team, and all personnel must meet the security and safety requirements of operating generation infrastructure.
  </p>
  <p>
    Across the industrial portfolio, 24/7 operational flexibility is not an optional service feature — it is a baseline requirement. Industrial facilities do not schedule their maintenance windows around business hours, and cleaning coverage during critical maintenance periods must be available when the maintenance window occurs, not when it is convenient.
  </p>

  <h2>Compliance and Standards</h2>
  <p>
    Industrial cleaning operations within CPC's portfolio operate under the following compliance framework:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>ISO 45001:2018</strong>. Occupational Health and Safety Management System, providing the documented risk framework within which site-specific hazard assessments, method statements and incident management procedures operate.</li>
    <li><strong>Work Health and Safety Act requirements</strong>. State-jurisdiction WHS legislation obligations, including the duty of care requirements that apply to cleaning operators working in environments with identified high-risk construction and industrial hazards.</li>
    <li><strong>Permit-to-work integration</strong>. Cleaning activities that occur in areas governed by the client's permit-to-work system are coordinated with the permit holder. Supervisors are trained on the permit-to-work requirements of each specific facility type where this applies.</li>
    <li><strong>Hazardous substance and chemical management</strong>. Safety Data Sheet (SDS) documentation for all cleaning chemicals used on site, with storage, handling and disposal procedures that comply with the hazardous substance requirements of the specific facility.</li>
    <li><strong>Site-specific induction compliance</strong>. All workforce members complete the client site's mandatory safety induction and any additional training required by the site's safety management system before commencing work.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Outcomes</h2>
  <p>
    The sustained multi-site industrial portfolio is the primary outcome evidence. Industrial cleaning contracts are not renewed when safety performance is inadequate — the consequences of a safety incident in a high-risk industrial environment are too significant for clients to continue with a provider who cannot demonstrate ongoing WHS compliance.
  </p>
  <p>
    Operational continuity across the portfolio — including during the most demanding periods such as planned shutdowns and unplanned maintenance windows — demonstrates the 24/7 mobilisation capability that industrial clients require. The ability to provide cleaning coverage during an unscheduled shutdown at a remote facility, at short notice, within the client's safety management framework, is the capability that distinguishes an industrial cleaning provider from a commercial one.
  </p>
  <p>
    For procurement teams evaluating industrial cleaning capability, the reference questions are: which specific facility types does the provider currently service, what are their documented safety performance records in those environments, and can they demonstrate permit-to-work integration experience in comparable facilities? These are the questions that reveal genuine industrial capability, not the questions that reveal management system certifications held.
  </p>

